# Public Prosecutor _v_ GEO  

### \[2022\] SGDC 134

Criminal Procedure and Sentencing – Sentencing

\[LawNet Editorial Note: An appeal to this decision has been filed in MA 9112/2022/01-02.\]

15 June 2022

### District Judge Lee Lit Cheng:

1       The accused is a 48-year-old man with Human Immunodeficiency Virus Infection (“HIV Infection”). He was charged with two counts under s 23(1) read with s 23(3) of the Infectious Diseases Act (Cap 137, 2003 Rev Ed) (“IDA”) for engaging in sexual activity with another person without first informing the person of the risk of contracting HIV Infection from him. The offence is punishable with a fine not exceeding $50,000 or imprisonment for a term not exceeding 10 years or both.

2       The first offence (_vide_ DSC-900763-2021) was committed by the accused on 10 October 2019 in relation to the first victim (“V1”). While investigations relating to the first offence were ongoing, the accused committed the second offence involving the second victim (“V2”) on 24 April 2021 (_vide_ DSC-900903-2021).

3       The accused pleaded guilty to DSC-900903-2021 and the other charge was taken into consideration for the purpose of sentencing. The accused sought a high fine or a fine coupled with a short custodial term not exceeding three months, while the Prosecution sought a sentence of at least 24 months’ imprisonment.

4       Applying the sentencing framework in _GCP v Public Prosecutor and another matter_ <span class="citation">\[2019\] 5 SLR 626</span> (“_GCP_”), I sentenced the accused to 12 months’ imprisonment.

5       Both the Prosecution and the accused have appealed against the sentence.

## Facts

6       The accused was diagnosed with HIV Infection in 2017. Upon being diagnosed, an officer of the National Centre for Infectious Diseases informed him that prior to engaging in any sexual activity with any person, the accused was required to inform the person of his HIV Infection regardless of his viral load and his perceived risk to others. He was also told that he would be liable to a fine of up to $10,000 and imprisonment up to 10 years if he failed to do so.

### The first offence (the TIC charge)

7       On 10 October 2019, the accused engaged in sexual activity with V1 without first informing V1 of the risk of contracting HIV Infection from him and without obtaining V1’s voluntary agreement to accept that risk.

8       On 11 October 2019, the Ministry of Health (“MOH”) commenced investigations against the accused for an offence under s 23 of the IDA after the police referred V1’s complaint to MOH.

### The second offence (the proceeded charge)

9       On 23 April 2021, while investigations for the first offence under s 23 of the IDA were ongoing, the accused engaged in sexual activity with V2 without first informing V2 of the risk of contracting HIV Infection from him and without obtaining V2’s voluntary agreement to accept that risk. The accused placed V2’s penis (without a condom) in his mouth.

10     On 30 September 2021, the police informed MOH of V2’s complaint that he had been sexually assaulted by the accused who performed oral sex on V2 without first informing V2 of the risk of HIV transmission.

### The accused’s risk of transmission

11     It was not disputed that the accused’s risk of transmission at the time of the second offence on 23 April 2021 was likely to be effectively zero. The accused’s viral load tests taken at six-monthly intervals from 24 November 2017 to 13 January 2022 consistently showed that his viral load was “Not Detected”, except for the test taken on 27 July 2021. In particular, the results of the tests taken before and after the second offence were as follows:

12     The victims did not contract HIV Infection from the accused.

## The parties’ submissions

13     The Prosecution submitted that the case fell in the higher end of Band 1 of the _GCP_ sentencing framework and sought a sentence of at least 24 months’ imprisonment.

14     Counsel for the accused submitted that the case fell in the lower end of Band 1 of the _GCP_ sentencing framework and sought a high fine or a fine coupled with a short term of imprisonment of no more than three months.

## My decision

15     The _GCP_ sentencing framework sets out the sentencing bands which apply to first-time offenders who claim trial to an offence under s 23(1) read with s 23(3) of the IDA:

![](data:image;base64,)

16     The first step of the framework requires the sentencing court to identify the appropriate sentencing band and the starting point within the band with reference to the parameters of harm and culpability. Where HIV is not transmitted, the framework places equal weight on harm (being the risk of HIV transmission) and culpability.

17     In the second step, the court may make adjustments to the indicative starting point sentence with regard to any other aggravating or mitigating factor.

18     Applying the _GCP_ sentencing framework to the present case, I first determined that the risk of transmission was at the lowest end of Band 1, as it was likely that there was effectively no risk of HIV transmission in this case.

19     Next, I considered the degree of culpability. In _GCP_, See Kee Oon J stated (at \[87\]) that the failure to comply with one’s disclosure obligations even after having been informed of them would generally place the offender’s culpability at the medium to high end of the “low culpability” range in Band 1. In this regard, counsel for the accused submitted that the failure to disclose should not automatically place the offender’s culpability at the medium to high end of the “low culpability” range in Band 1, as the failure to disclose is “part of the offence”[\[note: 1\]](#Ftn_1) and therefore should not also be regarded as an aggravating factor. This appears to be a misunderstanding of See J’s guidance. See J did not say that the failure to disclose _per se_ is an aggravating factor; it is _knowing_ non-disclosure after having been informed of the disclosure obligation that is culpability-increasing.

20     It was also raised in mitigation that the accused did not disclose the risk of transmission to V2 because “he knew that there was **no risk of transmission at all**”.[\[note: 2\]](#Ftn_2) It is not entirely accurate to say that the accused _knew_ at the time of the second offence on 23 April 2021 that there was _no risk of transmission at all_, as the last viral load test was taken three months prior on 26 January 2021 and he did not know the results of the upcoming test in July 2021. At best, the accused could only have told V2 that the risk of transmission was _likely to be zero_ as his viral load had consistently been “Not Detected” since 24 November 2017, including the latest test taken three months ago. In any event, the fact that the risk of transmission was practically zero is not mitigating; it is merely not aggravating. By the accused’s own account, he withheld disclosure because he was “\[a\]fraid of the stigma against HIV”.[^3] In other words, the accused was afraid that V2 would refuse to engage in sexual activity with him if V2 knew that he had HIV Infection. It was in no way mitigating for the accused to deny V2 of the freedom to choose whether to engage in sexual activity with the accused even though no viral load was detected.

21     I therefore see no reason to depart from the guidance given by the High Court in _GCP_ that the degree of culpability for knowing non-disclosure would fall in the medium to high end of the low culpability range in Band 1. Apart from failing to comply with his disclosure obligation even after having been informed of them, the accused had also committed the second offence while he was being investigated for the first offence. This demonstrates a lack of regard for the law and pushes the accused’s culpability to the top end of Band 1. To be clear, the fact that a person is being investigated for an offence does not necessarily mean that he has committed the offence. At this stage of the assessment, I have only considered the fact that the accused was being _investigated for_ the first offence and not that he had _committed_ the first offence.

22     The sentences in Band 1 range from a fine to two years’ imprisonment. As equal weight is to be given to harm and culpability, I arrived at an indicative starting point sentence of 12 months’ imprisonment after balancing the risk of transmission at the lowest end of Band 1 with the degree of culpability at the top end of Band 1.

23     The final step was to consider other aggravating and mitigating factors. The accused was a first offender who had pleaded guilty to the charge. No further adjustment to the indicative starting point sentence was needed as the mitigating effect of the accused’s plea of guilt was offset by the fact that another similar charge involving a separate victim was taken into consideration for the purpose of sentencing. I therefore sentenced the accused to 12 months’ imprisonment.

24     The Prosecution’s assessment of harm and culpability – risk of transmission is effectively zero and culpability is at the higher end of Band 1 –is in line with my finding. With equal weight to be given to harm and culpability, I fail to see how one could arrive at a sentence of 24 months’ imprisonment.

25     I am also unable to agree with the Defence’s submissions that the case falls in the low end of Band 1 such that a high fine or a fine coupled with a short custodial term would suffice. I have explained why I assessed the accused’s culpability to be at the top end of Band 1. It is not possible for the case to land in the low end of Band 1 unless more weight is placed on harm than culpability.

26     The High Court in _GCP_ had explicitly rejected submissions by the respondent in that case asking for more weight to be placed on harm rather than culpability. See J explained (at \[73\]) that it would be more appropriate for harm and culpability to be given equal weight where HIV transmission did not result:

> While the general purpose of the provisions in the IDA on HIV may be said to be the prevention and control of the spread of the virus, the Parliamentary debates also indicate that s 23 IDA is aimed at deterring HIV individuals from placing others at risk through irresponsible behaviour. Moreover, the significance of potential harm in the sentencing matrix for s 23(1) offences is diminished by the fact that the harm caused is to some extent binary: either one contracts HIV or one does not. While the extent of the risk of transmission is certainly significant, it is not determinative in that it is clear that one may contract HIV from a single sexual act, even if the risks of doing so are extremely low. I therefore do not see a clear and principled reason why more weight should be placed on either harm or culpability in sentencing for s 23(1) offences.

27     Finally, counsel for the accused submitted that the present case is clearly less aggravating than the offender in _GCP_. I agree. In that case, the risk of transmission was assessed to be between Band 1 and Band 2 (given the offender’s viral load and the fact that the offender had engaged in unprotected penile-anal and penile-oral intercourse with the victim on multiple occasions), and the offender’s level of culpability was also heightened because he knew of his obligation to disclose but did not comply. The offender in _GCP_ was sentenced to 24 months’ imprisonment. In my view, the accused’s sentence of 12 months’ imprisonment is consonant with the sentence ordered in _GCP_.

## Conclusion

28     Section 23(1) of the IDA mandates disclosure by a person with HIV Infection, regardless of his viral load or risk of transmission, so that the infected person’s sexual partner has an opportunity to decide whether he _voluntarily_ agrees to accept the risk of contracting HIV Infection. By placing equal weight on harm and culpability where HIV transmission does not occur, the _GCP_ sentencing framework seeks to ensure that there is sufficient deterrence for offenders who deliberately withhold disclosure to avoid being rejected by partners who are unwilling to accept the risk. Given the accused’s level of culpability, a sentence of 12 months’ imprisonment is appropriate.

29     Bail pending appeal was offered but the accused was not bailed out as at the date of this judgment.
